sbol:Collection.dcterms:title: iGEM Parts Registry
sbol:Collection.dcterms:description: The iGEM Registry is a growing collection of genetic parts that can be mixed and matched to build synthetic biology devices and systems. As part of the synthetic biology community's efforts to make biology easier to engineer, it provides a source of genetic parts to iGEM teams and academic labs.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_M36239
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: This part is designed to sense epinephrine, and generate a PoPS signal in response. The QseB and QseC genes are connected to a constitutive promoter, and so will be constantly expressing the QseB and QseC proteins, which will creates the adrenergic receptors (QseC) on the surface of the cell as well as the signaling molecules activated when the receptor is activated (QseB). When epinephrine is detected by QseC, it autophosphorylates, which in turn will phosphorylate QseB. This, in turn, will bind to the flhDC promoter, activating it. This will cause a PoPS signal to be produced, which can be used with an actuator. It is important to note that QseC may be activated not only by epinephrine, but also norepinephrine and Auto-Inducer 3 (AI3).
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Lawerence Xing and Andres Gaeta
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: The promoters, bicistronic RBS, and transcriptional terminators were all sourced from BioFab. The QseB and QSeC coding sequences were taken from, EcoCyc, which documented the entire genome of E. Coli. The flhDC was also taken from EcoCyc's website.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: In order to ensure as high a PoPS signal as possible, we used the strongest promoters, RBS, and transcriptional terminators available.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_M36230
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: A constitutive promoter obtained from BIOFAB.org. It is in the top 80th percentile of BIOFAB promoters in terms of expression strength, as measured by mean fluorescence per cell.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Lawrence Xing
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: BIOFAB part id: apFAB85 BIOFAB construct id: pFAB329

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_M36236
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription:
This is a 5' UTR that uses bicistronic junction architecture to tightly control translation. It contains two ribosome binding sites: one to control the gene of interest, and another to synthesize a short leader protein. The latter cistron's translation prevents the former RBS from forming a secondary structure with the gene of interest.
NOTE: The part BBa_M36282 is identical to this one and was submitted by a member of the same group. It is recommended that the instructors of this group deprecate one of the duplicates.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Lawrence Xing

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_M36231
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: QseB is a quorum sensing response regulator derived from Escherichia coli. When phosphorylated by the histidine kinase QseC, QseB binds to the flhDC promoter and induces transcription of the downstream gene.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Lawrence Xing
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: The design was codon optimized and designed to exclude restriction sites for BsaI.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_M36234
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: QseC is a quorum sensing histidine kinase derived from Escherichia coli. It autophosphorylates when bound by either of the catecholamines epinephrine and norepinephrine, or one of the autoinducers AI-2 and AI-3. Activated QseC then phosphorylates the cognate response regulator QseB, which induces flhDC.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Lawrence Xing
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: The design was codon optimized and designed to exclude restriction sites for BsaI.
